1. CRACKS — the SPT as lightning the pulse reveals. I saw a clear, cheap choice for the lightning path and gave it a go: MIDPOINT DISPLACEMENT (a fractional-Brownian bridge). Each SPT edge — read straight off `pointMesh()`'s tree flags, rooted at the i-dot — becomes a filament: recursively offset each segment's midpoint perpendicular to itself by a random amount, halving the amplitude every level (5 levels ≈ 32 segments). That yields exactly what you described: a strong, mostly-linear spine that is irregular but unistroke, its jaggedness self-similar. On top of the spine I hang one or two faint OFFSHOOTS on the longer edges (a short displaced branch veering off an interior vertex, no new node), for the ramification. Each filament is seeded from its endpoints, so it's stable across frames and across rebuilds (it re-forms when you drag a dot). New fixed layer `#crack-canvas` (z-index 12, above the cones and copy, under the logo). Reveal: a `crackR` radius from the i-dot grows with the main front — a filament point lights once the front reaches its distance from the root and stays lit; the growing tips flash brighter at the front. Invisible through the whole gather (crackR 0), full and permanent once the wave clears (crackR ∞). Colour is the site gold with a hot near-white core, so it reads electric. The straight-line fallback wasn't needed — say the word if you'd rather see plain segments to compare.

2. CONES — your exact procedure, and the duplicate glow gone. Rebuilt the target logic per 2.1/2.2: a reflective rectangle counts when at least one of its FOUR CORNERS is within 2·r₋ (I switched the reach test from box-edge distance to the corner test you specified). Each qualifying rectangle contributes ONE angular window — the smallest interval spanning all four of its corners (in reach or not, so we never take a partial subset). All windows are unioned into disjoint arcs, and the point glows ONE flat sector per arc. The cause of "some directions way more pronounced" was a leftover per-rectangle brighter core drawn on top of the union — overlapping rectangles stacked those. It's deleted; the union is now uniform, no direction lit twice. Inside a box → radial (stuff all around); nothing in reach → the bare radial bulb.

3. MAGENTA GLOW — every gold object, for inspection. Every reflective ink unit is reduced to a centre + half-extents and exposed as `window.LITGOLD` (reflect.js): one entry per WHOLE WORD (its data-g group, so "Barreiro" is one, not three), per section rule, per line-art icon, per photo-frame run. main.js casts a loud magenta glow from each centre as an ELLIPSE — the radial glow stretched to the object's own x/y extent, so a single source covers a word exactly as you wanted. It's on this turn only, for you to check the set. One capture note: the glow layers are viewport-fixed (page-anchored by scroll), so a full-page shot only paints the top screenful at once — on the live page each section's magenta shows as you scroll to it.

